      "content": "Hark! A good question, though it sounds like you're trying to navigate a maze of numbers while a goblin named \"Goblin of the Numbers\" is currently trying to eat your mortgage calculator.\n\nYou ask about the difference between a Fixed Rate Mortgage (FRM) and an Adjustable Rate Mortgage (ARM). In the grand scheme of things, an FRM is like a goblin who has been given a permanent, unchanging job title and a salary that never changes, whereas an ARM is like a goblin who has been given a temporary job title and a salary that is subject to a sudden, unpredictable economic shift.\n\nLet's break down the monthly payment changes over the first five years, because that is where the goblins of the market will be most active.\n\n**The Fixed Rate Mortgage (FRM):**\nThink of an FRM as a goblin who has been given a contract that says, \"Your salary will be exactly $X every single month, forever.\" If the economy gets a little bit of a bump, or if the goblin decides to take a nap, your payment stays exactly the same. It is the goblin of stability. If you are looking for a goblin who will never leave you",
